Clustering Heatmap - RNA-Seq

CCDL for ALSF

Purpose: This notebook illustrates one way that you can use harmonized data from refine.bio in downstream analyses.

TODO: This introduction section will be revamped when the intro to an example analysis (#122: https://github.com/AlexsLemonade/refinebio-examples/pull/122) gets more polished/determined.

1) Install libraries

This script uses the R package DESeq2 for normalization and the R package pheatmap for clustering and creating a heatmap.
Citation: Love, M.I., Huber, W., Anders, S. Moderated estimation of fold change and dispersion for RNA-Seq data with DESeq2 Genome Biology 15(12):550 (2014)
Citation: Raivo Kolde (2019). pheatmap: Pretty Heatmaps. R package version 1.0.12. https://CRAN.R-project.org/package=pheatmap

if (!("pheatmap" %in% installed.packages())) {
  # Install pheatmap
  install.packages("pheatmap", update = FALSE)
}

if (!("DESeq2" %in% installed.packages())) {
  # Install DESeq2
  BiocManager::install("DESeq2", update = FALSE)
}

Attach the pheatmap and DESeq2 libraries:

2) Import and set up data

Data downloaded from refine.bio include a metadata [tab separated values (tsv)] (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tab-separated_values) file and a data tsv file. This chunk of code will read the both tsv files and add them as data.frame objects to your environment.

The data that we downloaded from refine.bio for this analysis has 24 samples (obtained from 6 mice with 4 technical replicates for each mouse), containing RNA-sequencing results for Group 3 and 4 medulloblastoma orthotopic xenograft mice with and without digoxin treatment.

You can download this dataset by going to the following link and clicking Download Now: https://www.refine.bio/experiments/SRP150101/transcriptome-analysis-of-group-3-and-4-medulloblastoma-orthotopic-xenograft-mice-with-digoxin-treatment

# Read in metadata tsv file
metadata <- readr::read_tsv(file.path(
  "data", # Replace with path to your metadata file
  "metadata_SRP150101.tsv" # Replace with the name of your metadata file
)) %>%
  # We only need the three variables from the metadata for this notebook
  dplyr::select(refinebio_accession_code, refinebio_title, refinebio_treatment)

Lets take a look at the metadata object that we read into the R environment.

head(metadata)

We are going to manipulate the metadata and add variables with the information that we would like to use to annotate the heatmaps.

metadata <- metadata %>%
  dplyr::mutate(
    # Create a variable to store the treatment group information
    groups = dplyr::case_when(
      refinebio_treatment == "no treatment" ~ "control",
      TRUE ~ "digoxin"
      # Replace with group names relevant to your data
    ),
    # Create a variable to hold the sample summary information
    # (excluding the lane information)
    sample_info_summary = gsub("(_L).*", "", refinebio_title),
    # Create a variable to store the mouse ids
    mouse_id = stringr::word(refinebio_title, sep = "-|_", 2, 3),
    # Create a variable to store the subgroup information
    subgroup = dplyr::case_when(
      startsWith(mouse_id, "2555MB") ~ "group 3",
      startsWith(mouse_id, "1078MB") ~ "group 4",
      TRUE ~ "unknown"
    )
  )

Now lets ensure that the metadata and data are in the same sample order.

# Make the data in the order of the metadata
df <- df %>% dplyr::select(metadata$refinebio_accession_code)

# Check if this is in the same order
all.equal(colnames(df), metadata$refinebio_accession_code)
[1] TRUE

3) Choose genes of interest

Although you may want to create a heatmap including all of the genes in the set, alternatively, the heatmap could be created using only genes of interest. For this example, we will sort genes by variance, but there are many alternative criterion by which you may want to sort your genes eg fold change, t-statistic, membership to a particular gene ontology, so on.

# Calculate the variance for each gene
variances <- apply(df, 1, var)

# Determine the upper quartile variance cutoff value
upper_var <- quantile(variances, 0.75)

# Subset the data choosing only genes whose variances are in the upper quartile
df_by_var <- df %>%
  dplyr::filter(variances > upper_var)

How are our technical replicates clustering together?

We know that our dataset includes technical replicates because we have replicate data which has been split across lanes of sequencing from the same animal, sample, and library (we were able to determine this information using the metadata and associated article which can be found at the following link: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30355798/).

Before we look at the biological clustering of our data, we should first determine how our technical replicates cluster together and how that may affect our biological interpretation.

4) Create a DESeqDataset

A DESeqDataSet object is required to carry out the normalization step that you will see later using a function from the DESeq2 package. This chunk of code will turn the data.frame (or matrix) into a DESeqDataSet object.

# The `DESeqDataSetFromMatrix` function needs the values to be converted to
# integers
## TODO: Link to explanation about `DESeqDataSet` in the RNA-seq header section
df_by_var <- df_by_var %>%
  # Mutate numeric variables to be integers
  dplyr::mutate_if(is.numeric, round)

# Create a `DESeqDataSet` object
dds <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(
  countData = df_by_var,
  colData = metadata,
  design = ~ refinebio_treatment # Replace with an appropriate design variable for your analysis
)

5) Prepare the metadata

We are going to format the metadata to be used for annotation on the heatmap.

# Let's prepare the annotation data.frame for the uncollapsed `DESeqData` set
# object which will be used to create the technical replicates heatmap
technical_annotation_df <- metadata %>%
  # We do not need this information for annotating the technical replicates heatmap
  dplyr::select(-c("sample_info_summary", "refinebio_title")) %>%
  # The `pheatmap` function requires that the rownames of our annotation object
  # matches the column names of our `DESeaDataSet` object
  tibble::column_to_rownames("refinebio_accession_code")

6) Define a minimum counts cutoff

We are going to do some pre-filtering to keep only rows with 10 or more reads total. We want to filter out the genes that have not been expressed or that have low expression counts because we want to remove any possible noise from our data before we normalize the data and create our heatmap.

# Let's take a look at the distribution of counts first

# Sum up the counts for each gene -- which means we want the sum of counts for
# each row as the rows represent gene data and the columns represent sample data
# in our dataset
technical_count_sums <- data.frame(count = rowSums(counts(dds)))

# Create a density plot using the sums
ggplot2::ggplot(technical_count_sums, ggplot2::aes(x = count)) +
  ggplot2::geom_density() +
  ggplot2::geom_vline(ggplot2::aes(xintercept = 10), # This line represents the current cutoff of 10
                      color = "blue",
                      linetype = "dashed") +
  ggplot2::geom_vline(ggplot2::aes(xintercept = mean(count)), # This line represents the mean count value
                                   color = "red",
                                   linetype = "dashed")

# Define a minimum counts cutoff and filter `DESeqDataSet` object to include
# only rows that have counts above the cutoff
genes_to_keep <- rowSums(counts(dds)) >= 10
dds <- dds[genes_to_keep, ]

7) Perform DESeq2 normalization

We are going to use a function from the DESeq2 package to normalize the data.

# Normalize the data in the `DESeqDataSet` object using the
# `normTransform` function from the `DESEq2` R package
## TODO: Add a note/link to section in documentation on why we use
# `normTransform` vs `vst` and `rlog`
ntd_technical <- normTransform(dds)

8) Create a heatmap

To further customize the heatmap, see a vignette for a guide at this link.

# Create and store the heatmap object
technical_pheatmap <-
  pheatmap(
    assay(ntd_technical),
    cluster_rows = FALSE, # Replace with `TRUE` to cluster heatmap by rows (genes in this case)
    cluster_cols = FALSE, # Replace with `TRUE` to cluster heatmap by columns (samples in this case)
    annotation_col = technical_annotation_df,
    main = "Technical Replicates Heatmap",
    colorRampPalette(c("deepskyblue",
                       "black",
                       "yellow"))(25
                       )
  )

Now that weve seen our replicates are fairly identical lets take a look at our experimental question.

How are our biological replicates clustering together?

4) Create a DESeqDataset

A DESeqDataSet object is required to carry out the normalization step that you will see later using a function from the DESeq2 package. This chunk of code will collapse the DESeqDataSet object that we created above to account for technical replicates.

# Collapse the replicates using the `collapseReplicates` function from the
# `DESEq2` package on the `DESeqDataSet` object we created in
# "Create a DESeqDataset" from the previous section -- this function combines
# the counts from the technical replicates in our dataset 
dds_collapsed <- collapseReplicates(dds, dds$sample_info_summary)

5) Prepare the metadata

# Now we need to collapse the metadata to match the collapsed `DESeqDataSet`
# object
biological_annotation_df <- metadata %>%
  # We do not need this information for annotating the biological replicates heatmap
  dplyr::select(-c("refinebio_title", "refinebio_accession_code")) %>%
  # Use `distinct()` to get rid of the duplicates created from removing the
  # variables above as we do not need to represent the technical replicates here
  dplyr::distinct() %>%
  # The `pheatmap` function requires that the rownames of our annotation object
  # matches the column names of our `DESeaDataSet` object
  tibble::column_to_rownames("sample_info_summary")

6) Define a minimum counts cutoff

# Let's take a look at the distribution of counts for the collapsed data

# Sum up the counts for each gene -- which means we want the sum of counts for
# each row
biological_count_sums <- data.frame(count = rowSums(counts(dds)))

# Create a density plot using the sums
ggplot2::ggplot(biological_count_sums, ggplot2::aes(x = count)) +
  ggplot2::geom_density() +
  ggplot2::geom_vline(ggplot2::aes(xintercept = 10), # This line represents the current cutoff of 10
                      color = "blue",
                      linetype = "dashed") +
  ggplot2::geom_vline(ggplot2::aes(xintercept = mean(count)), # This line represents the mean count value
                                   color = "red",
                                   linetype = "dashed")

# Define a minimum counts cutoff and filter `DESeqDataSet` object to include
# only rows that have counts above the cutoff
genes_to_keep <- rowSums(counts(dds_collapsed)) >= 10
dds_collapsed <- dds_collapsed[genes_to_keep, ]

7) Perform DESeq2 normalization

# Now let's normalize the data for the collapsed counts using the
# `normTransform` function from the `DESeq2` package that we used in the
# previous section
ntd_biological <- normTransform(dds_collapsed)
  Note: levels of factors in the design contain characters other than
  letters, numbers, '_' and '.'. It is recommended (but not required) to use
  only letters, numbers, and delimiters '_' or '.', as these are safe characters
  for column names in R. [This is a message, not an warning or error]

8) Create a heatmap

# Now let's try creating a heatmap with the collapsed biological replicate data
biological_pheatmap <-
  pheatmap(
    assay(ntd_biological),
    cluster_rows = FALSE,
    cluster_cols = FALSE,
    annotation_col = biological_annotation_df,
    main = "Biological Replicates Heatmap",
    colorRampPalette(c("deepskyblue",
                       "black",
                       "yellow"))(25)
  )

In the heatmap above, it looks like not only do our technical replicates cluster together, but our biological replicates also cluster together (within the same technical environment).

9) Save heatmap as a png

You can easily switch this to save to a jpeg or tiff by changing the function and file name within the function to the respective file suffix.

# Open a png file
png(file.path(

biological_pheatmap
